 and the complexities of 'returning'. A close-up examination of 'belonging' and exclusion is made on a day-to-day basis. The book offers an approach to creating poems and literary texts constituted by experiencing multiple places, developing a model of polyvalent belonging known as 'polysituatedness'. It works as a companion volume to Kinsella's earlier Manchester University Press critical work, Disclosed Poetics: Beyond Landscape to Lyricism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPlace (Philosophy) in literature. 0aPoetics. 0aSetting (Literature). 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aAgoras.  aCollaboration.  aPlace.  aPoetics.  aPoetry.  aPraxis.  aactivism.1 aKinsella, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611336840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526113368423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526113368/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles